Intepretatiton of the Residuals vs Fittedplot.

The Residuals vs Fittedplot indicates our linear regression model has heteroscedasticity.There is an incorrect setting of our model function form. If the exponential curve model is mistakenly set as a linear model, the error tends to increase. Therefore, we should apply log() to the salary variable. Take the logarithm of salary to reduce the heteroscedasticity of our model.

Part II : Hot Hand Hypothesis Testing

Conditional Probability Approach

* From a birds eye point of view:

What is your impression on what the data is saying?

The table lists the probability of hit as well as conditional probability of hit given a previous miss or hit for each player. Based on simple observation, we dont think the data indicates the existence of the hot hand #### Just from examination, which players seem to exhibit the hot hand and which ones do not? Player B seem to be the one mostly likely to exhibit hot hand. And all the other players dont exhibit the hot hand. #### What is your logical reasoning? If P{hit|1 hit} > P{hit}, it indicates that the player has a higher probabilty of scoring given scored in the previous attempt. Since player B is the only one of the listed players that has P{hit|1 hit} > P{hit}, we think playerB might have the Hot Hand.

* Statistical point of view:

We performed a single side compare mean test (mean of P(hit) and mean of P(hit|hit) of 9 players) and below is the test result

Pairwise mean comparisons (t-test)
Data      : from_clipboard 
Variables : P_hit_, P_hit_1_hit_ 
Samples   : independent 
Confidence: 0.95 
Adjustment: None 

               mean n n_missing    sd    se    me
       P_hit_ 0.517 9         0 0.052 0.017 0.040
 P_hit_1_hit_ 0.502 9         0 0.048 0.016 0.037

 Null hyp.               Alt. hyp.               diff  p.value  
 P_hit_ = P_hit_1_hit_   P_hit_ < P_hit_1_hit_   0.014 0.725    

Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

What is the null hypothesis (the something else)? What are you hoping to show (alternative hypothesis)?

Null hypothesis: P(hit) = P(hit|hit)
Alternative hypothesis: P(hit) < P(hit|hit)

How much data do you have here?

We have the probability of hit, conditional probability of hit given a previous miss or hit of 9 players.

What distribution is appropriate?

We think a t distribution is appropriate for this hypothesis test

What conclusions can you draw from your test?

Since the p value of this hypothesis testing is 0.725, we do not reject the null hypothesis

Streaks Approach

Based on our simulation model, we filled out the table with missing values as below

In order to test whether the actual run numbers were substantially less than the mean it was first prudent to take a t.test of each of the sample distributions as compared to the actual number of runs. This test would significantly distinguish the actual run number from the simulation mean but would not provide enough proof on its own that the run number was low enough to provide credence to the hot hand theory. We cast our net pretty wide to be sure the actual run number was as far away from the mean as we could. Notably 3 were significantly distinguishable from the mean but at least did not provide compelling proof. One had a difference between the actual score and the simulated mean of only 1.9 runs. The only interesting note here is once again B, which has an estimated difference of about 10 runs. This is in line with previous statistics.

Part III : Critical Thinking

What might make the hot hand easier or more difficult to observe in either sport?

In basketball, a heat map showing where players shoot can be used to differentiate types of shots so difficult 3-point shots arent being compared to relatively more simple lay-ups. In baseball, players have fewer opportunities as well as times to hit the ball and also the time gap between each hit is longer, which makes data points sparse and harder for researchers to observe certain trends.

What would you need to do in order to establish that the hot hand exists in basketball?

Our best approach in both cases would be to create a more controlled environment to test a multitude of players attempting to make similar shots. In both cases a players ability to score a basket or hit may be controlled as much by the other team as the attempting player themselves. Limiting the number of variables will be key to attributing differences in scoring percentages to the hot hand theory itself. The baseball players may want to set up in a batting cage to increase the frequency of observations and control for the opposing team, while basketball players may want to run shooting drills rather than record shots in a tense game.

How would you build a regression model to try to establish that a hot hand exists?

We will build a Logistic regression. Each observation is one shot attempt of one player in various circumstances explained by the additional variables.
Response variable: hit or miss (1-0)
Dummy variable: hit/miss of previous attempt (1-0)
Categorical variable: type of match/ activity (drill, pitched game, blowout game [leads of 30 or more])
Categorical variable: type of attempt (3-point, lay-up, 2-point shot)
Numerical variable: number of attempts made previously (min = 0)
Numerical variable: number of successful hits in the run so far (min = 0)
Numerical variable: salary of the specific player (in 1000s)

What would be critical predictor variables?

The numerical variable stating the number of hits made previously would be the key variable here, with most of the others serving as control variables to differentiate different types of shots and eliminate potential confounds. In addition it would be interesting to see if the more skill based shots such as 3 pointers had a higher hot hand effect.

How much data would you need?

Ideally we would want to have a large amount of data for each player, at least 500 shots per player for a significant number of players. At least 1000 in this case. We would also want to control for different circumstances such as in game or performing drills. Keeping data separated by activity, player, and shot type would be essential. We can also have the data for a number of games, which will give us a chance to look at the players scoring patterns to help us identify whether a hot-hand kind of scenario really exists.
